    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - RECONDITIONING -
        CYLINDER SLEEVE FITTING PROCEDURE
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="hl4150604" svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="12">
        <title>CYLINDER SLEEVE FITTING PROCEDURE</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>Check crankcase counterbore depth using surface gauge
                <emph type="bold">SE-2515</emph>
                or a depth micrometer as follows:
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Surface Gauge Method</title>
            <para>Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150641">6.41</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">"Zero" the dial indicator on the crankcase deck.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Move the indicator onto the counterbore ledge and check the depth at four points.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150601.xml" xrefid="hl4150601">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>
                    for counterbore depth and maximum variation between the four measurement points.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If maximum variation between the four points exceeds specifications, resurface the
                    counterbore.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150641" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12119" filename="../figcg1/cg12119.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.41. Check Clearance Counterbore Depth Using Surface Gauge (SE-2515).</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Depth Micrometer Method</title>
            <para>Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150642">6.42</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the counterbore depth at four points around the crankcase counterbore.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Record the measurements.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="e415_HL4150601.xml" xrefid="hl4150601">"SPECIFICATIONS"</hotlnk>, and resurface
                    the counterbore if the maximum variation between measurement points is exceeded.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <para>Resurface the counterbore using the counterboring tool
                <emph type="bold">SE-2514</emph>
                along with the appropriate cutter head (
                <emph type="bold">No. 2200-55</emph>) as follows:
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The SE-2514 counterboring tool is a low profile tool which can be used in chassis. It is
                        manufactured by:
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Sargent Industries, Sweeney Division</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">6300 Stapelton South Drive</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Denver, Colorado</emph>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pre-set tool bit by placing a 0.008 in. to 0.010 in. feeler gauge on the O.D. of the
                    cutter head (
                    <emph type="bold">No. 2200-55</emph>). Push the tool bit out until it touches the feeler gauge. Lock
                    the tool bit in place using an Allen wrench (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150643">6.43</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the cutter head (
                    <emph type="bold">No. 2200-55</emph>) onto the driver unit and adapter plate of the counterboring
                    tool
                    <emph type="bold">SE-2514</emph>
                    (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150644">6.44</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150642" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12120" filename="../figcg1/cg12120.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.42. Check Crankcase Counterbore Depth Using a Depth Micrometer.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150643" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12121" filename="../figcg1/cg12121.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.43. Pre-Set Tool Bit.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150644" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11303" filename="../figcg1/cg11303.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.44. Counterboring Tool Components.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Raise the cutter head by pulling the plunger (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150644">6.44</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ) and lifting up on the handle. Mount the counterboring tool assembly to the crankcase as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150645">6.45</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Tighten the cap screw with washers finger-tight than apply 33 lb-ft. (45 Nm) torque.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lower the cutting head by pulling the plunger and
                    <emph type="underscr">SLOWLY</emph>
                    lower the drive unit handle until the cutter head contacts the counterbore ledge. (Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150646">6.46</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    )
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Set the depth of the cut using one of two methods.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">METHOD ONE</emph>
                        (Use graduated marks on tool) (See
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150647">6.47</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        )
                    </para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Loosen locking screw.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Rotate the adjusting nut in a counterclockwise direction until the nut contacts the driver
                            unit housing.
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Back off the adjusting nut by the amount of cut desired.</para>
                        <specpara>
                            <note>
                                <para>Each graduated marking equals 0.025 mm (0.001 in.). If 0.051 mm (0.002 in.)
                                    material is to be removed, you must back off the adjusting nut two marks.
                                </para>
                            </note>
                        </specpara>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Tighten the adjusting nut lock screw.</para>
                        <specpara>
                            <note>
                                <para>NEVER ATTEMPT TO REMOVE MORE THAN 0.051 mm (0.002 IN.) MATERIAL AT A TIME.</para>
                            </note>
                        </specpara>
                        <figure id="ef4150645" figsize="col-wide">
                            <graphic id="cg12122" filename="../figcg1/cg12122.webp" type="webp"/>
                            <caption>Figure 6.45. Mount Counterboring Tool to the Crankcase.</caption>
                        </figure>
                        <figure id="ef4150646" figsize="col-wide">
                            <graphic id="cg12123" filename="../figcg1/cg12123.webp" type="webp"/>
                            <caption>Figure 6.46. Lower Cutting Head into Counterbore.</caption>
                        </figure>
                        <figure id="ef4150647" figsize="col-wide">
                            <graphic id="cg12124" filename="../figcg1/cg12124.webp" type="webp"/>
                            <caption>Figure 6.47. Set Cutting Tool Depth Method One.</caption>
                        </figure>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">METHOD TWO</emph>
                        (Use feeler gauge) (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150648">6.48</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        )
                    </para>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Loosen locking screw.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Insert an appropriate size feeler gauge (0.002 in. max.) between the adjusting nut and
                            driver unit housing. Rotate the adjusting nut until the feeler gauge is just held in place.
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Tighten the locking screw and remove the feeler gauge.</para>
                    </step3>
                    <step3>
                        <para>Cut the counterbore by rotating the handle smoothly in a clockwise direction until the
                            unit turns freely and is bottomed out between the adjusting nut and the top of the driver
                            unit housing. Refer to
                            <emph type="bold">Figure
                                <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150649">6.49</hotlnk>
                            </emph>
                            .
                        </para>
                    </step3>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title></title>
            <para>Remeasure the counterbore depth once the counterbore has been resurfaced and cleaned up. Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl4150604">"CYLINDER SLEEVE FITTING PROCEDURE"</hotlnk>, step one in this section.
            </para>
            <para>Check cylinder sleeve protrusion as follows:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the cylinder bore and crankcase counterbore area.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>TO AVOID DAMAGE TO THE TOOL BIT, NEVER ROTATE COUNTERCLOCKWISE WHEN THE TOOL BIT IS IN
                            CONTACT WITH THE COUNTERBORE LEDGE.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place each sleeve in the crankcase without "O"-Rings. Clamp the sleeve down using three
                    holding adapters (made locally). Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150650">6.50</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150648" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12125" filename="../figcg1/cg12125.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.48. Set Cutting Tool Depth Method Two (Using Feeler Gauge).</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150649" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12126" filename="../figcg1/cg12126.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.49. Cut the Counterbore.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150650" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg5757" filename="../figcg5/cg5757.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.50. Cylinder Sleeve Holding Adapter Specifications.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the sleeve into its bore and install the holding adapters as shown in
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150651">6.51</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    . Fasten the holding adapters using grade 8 bolts and hardened washers. Tighten the bolts in three
                    stages as follows:
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">40 lbf-ft. (55 Nm)</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">80 lbf-ft. (110 Nm)</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">120 lb-ft. (165 Nm)</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using surface gauge
                    <emph type="bold">SE-2515</emph>, place the dial indicator tip on the cylinder sleeve flange. "Zero"
                    the indicator and move the block until the indicator tip drops off the flange to the crankcase deck.
                    Record reading (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150652">6.52</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Take readings at three points around the sleeve and use the average reading to determine
                            which shim(s), if any, is needed to bring cylinder sleeve protrusion within specification.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4150651" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12127" filename="../figcg1/cg12127.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.51. Tighten Holding Adapters.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150652" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12128" filename="../figcg1/cg12128.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.52. Measure Sleeve Protrusion.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Adjust the sleeve protrusion, as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove holding adapters and cylinder sleeve.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean the top deck of the crankcase and the cylinder sleeve counterbore.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the shim(s), as required to bring the protrusion above the crankcase deck
                        within specifications. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk document="e415_117.xml" xrefid="ef4150653">6.53</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Shims are available as a package consisting of the following:</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <table id="t4150610">
                        <tgroup cols="2">
                            <colspec colname="1" colwidth="65p"/>
                            <colspec colname="2" colwidth="157p"/>
                            <spanspec namest="1" nameend="2" spanname="s1t2"/>
                            <thead>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>Quantity</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>Shim Size</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                            </thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>2</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.051 mm (0.002 in.)</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>2</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.101 mm (0.004 in.)</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>1</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.254 mm (0.010 in.)</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>1</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.508 mm (0.020 in.)</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>2</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.816 mm (0.032 in.)</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                            </tbody>
                        </tgroup>
                    </table>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Follow cylinder sleeve installation instructions.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
